      "created_at": "2025-04-13T20:11:17.439Z",
      "cooked": "<p>Of course you can use short term goals, but see them as they are; a stepping stone to a long term goal.</p>\n<p>You can always do a short term goal as long as it doesn\u2019t deviate you from the path of the long term. That is, if you want to be the best you can, and do everything it takes.</p>\n<p>Maybe you don\u2019t like zone 2, there are more riders who just want to go fast. That is fine too. It doesn\u2019t take you to your best level, but maybe you are okee with that.<br>\nI get cyclists in my webinar sometimes who say to me, I understand what you are saying and I believe it is true, your offer is great too, but I don\u2019t want to do the work. I just want to ride.</p>\n<p>Every amateur has it\u2019s own version af that. Yes, I measure a lot of my food, but not everything and every day. Yes, I train hard, but I don\u2019t ride a 13000,- bike.</p>\n<p>There are always things we are not willing to do. You need to find the things you love to do to get better, and be at peace with the things you don\u2019t want to do.</p>\n<p>In my humble opinion you can/ should do both: slow and long vs short and intense.</p>\n<p>But no matter what you do: have fun</p>",
